03298nam a22004575i 9780773564633DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19941994xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735646337 a10.1515/97807735646332doi  a(DE-B1597)654871  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1059.7.E53bG74 1994eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a305.811/207131 aGreenhill, Pauline, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEthnicity in the Mainstream :bThree Studies of English Canadian Culture in Ontario /cPauline Greenhill. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Ethnic History ;v1900tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tEnglish Immigrants’ Narratives of Discourse Entitlement -- tMorris: An “English Male Dance Tradition” -- tSelling Stratford as an English Place -- tAnthropology and I: Participating in the Creation of Culture -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGreenhill presents three studies from the perspective of a folklorist and within the framework of feminist analysis. Loosely linked by the theme of power and discussion of carnivalesque elements of traditional and popular culture, these studies examine immigrants' narratives about adjusting to life in Canada; Morris dancing as practised by Forest City Morris of London, Ontario; and actions and responses of promoters and residents to the development of the Shakespeare festival in Stratford, Ontario. Greenhill notes that because the English are perceived as lacking carnivalesque traditions, their position vis-à-vis other ethnic groups has been defined solely in terms of power, and demonstrates that concepts of power and entitlement are inextricably bound up in English self-definition. She concludes by examining the implications for social scientific practice of an insider studying her own culture and the political ramifications of such studies for a pluralistic, multicultural society such as Canada. Greenhill's methods, concepts, and conclusions have much to offer practitioners in the fields of folklore, Canadian studies, ethnic studies, anthropology, and women's studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356463340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773564633423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773564633/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles